<style|generic>

<\body>
  <documentclass|article> <usepackage|amsmath,amsfonts,amssymb>

  Given a sequence of orthonormal polynomials within a Reproducing Kernel
  Hilbert Space (RKHS) associated with a positive definite kernel, these
  polynomials not only converge uniformly to the kernel function but also
  embody the RKHS's structure and purpose. They form a crucial subset of the
  RKHS, uniquely facilitating the representation and approximation of
  functions within this space, especially significant in the context of
  stochastic process representation via the Karhunen-Lo×ve theorem.

  To accurately reflect the distinguished characteristics and the integral
  role of these polynomials in the RKHS, they are termed the
  <with|font-series|bold|"Orthogonal Polynomial Spectral Reproducing Basis">.
  This nomenclature comprehensively highlights:

  <\enumerate>
    <item><with|font-series|bold|Orthogonal>: Denoting their orthogonality
    within the space, a fundamental property enabling efficient
    representation and approximation.

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Polynomial>: Specifying their mathematical
    form, indicating the use of polynomial functions as the basis elements.

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Spectral>: Relating to the spectral analysis
    aspect, indicating a connection to the spectral properties of the
    associated covariance operator and their derivation process.

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Reproducing Basis>: Emphasizing their
    capacity to exploit the reproducing property of the kernel, signifying
    that these polynomials are specifically designed or identified to
    represent functions in the RKHS optimally.
  </enumerate>

  This designation, <with|font-series|bold|"Orthogonal Polynomial Spectral
  Reproducing Basis">, not only captures their mathematical role and origin
  but also underlines their functionality and utility in the analysis and
  representation of functions within the RKHS.
</body>

